1. BSON vs JSON — MongoDB stores BSON; it supports ObjectId, Date, Binary
   (JSON has no Date type or binary types)

2. The _id field — automatically created ObjectId; indexed by default;
   immutable after creation

3. Collection scans vs Index scans — COLLSCAN reads all docs (slow at scale);
   IXSCAN uses an index (fast)

4. Atomic operations — single-document operations are always atomic;
   multi-document atomicity requires transactions

5. Transactions — MongoDB 4.0+ supports multi-document ACID transactions;
   needed for bank transfers, inventory updates across collections

6. Sharding — horizontal scaling by partitioning data across multiple servers;
   shard key choice is critical

7. Replica Sets — 3+ node HA clusters; primary handles writes;
   secondaries replicate and can serve reads

8. Write Concern — controls durability: w:1 (primary ack), w:'majority' (safer)

9. Read Preference — where reads go: primary, secondary, nearest

10. TTL Indexes — automatically delete documents after a time period:
    createIndex({ createdAt: 1 }, { expireAfterSeconds: 3600 })

// ❌ MISTAKE 1: Missing index on a frequently queried field
db.orders.find({ 'customer.email': 'alice@example.com' })
// Fix: db.orders.createIndex({ 'customer.email': 1 })

// ❌ MISTAKE 2: Returning all fields when you only need a few
db.books.find({})  // Fix: db.books.find({}, { title: 1, price: 1 })

// ❌ MISTAKE 3: Using $where (JavaScript eval — slow and insecure)
db.books.find({ $where: 'this.price > 10' })  // Fix: db.books.find({ price: { $gt: 10 } })

// ❌ MISTAKE 4: $lookup before $match in aggregation
db.books.aggregate([{ $lookup: { ... } }, { $match: { inStock: true } }])
// Fix: $match FIRST
db.books.aggregate([{ $match: { inStock: true } }, { $lookup: { ... } }])

// ❌ MISTAKE 5: Large skip() values for pagination
db.books.find().skip(10000).limit(20)  // slow — walks 10000 docs
// Fix: range-based pagination with { _id: { $gt: lastSeenId } }

// Write with majority concern — survives primary failure
await db.collection('orders').insertOne(doc, { writeConcern: { w: 'majority' } });

// Read concern: 'local' = read from current node (may be slightly stale)
// Read concern: 'majority' = read only data confirmed by majority (stronger)
await db.collection('orders').findOne(filter, { readConcern: { level: 'majority' } });

const changeStream = db.collection('orders').watch();

for await (const change of changeStream) {
  console.log(change.operationType);  // 'insert', 'update', 'delete'
  console.log(change.fullDocument);   // the document that changed
  // React: send a push notification, invalidate cache, etc.
}
